<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Malaysia Sign Joint Statement on Developing Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Malaysia on Sunday signed a
joint statement on developing bilateral cooperation, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed by Iraqi Minister of Industry and
Minerals Adnan Abd al-Majid al-Ani and visiting Malaysian Foreign
Minister Syed Hamid Albar.
</P>
<P>
The statement touched upon the issues of expanding economic,
trade, oil, agricultural, industrial, transportation and scientific
cooperation between Iraq and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The next round of meetings of the Joint Iraqi-Malaysian Trade
And Economic Committee will be held next year in Kuala Lumpur,
capital of Malaysia, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded fifth round of meetings has been very
important in reactivating cooperation between the two countries,
said the Iraqi minister.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement reflected the readiness and keenness of both
Iraq and Malaysia to develop all-round ties, al-Ani added.
</P>
<P>
AlBar expressed belief that trade and economic ties between Iraq
and Malaysia will soon witness major steps forward, terming the
statement as "a true and significant step" to expand bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Declaring his visit to Baghdad "important and fruitful," he said
it will surely push the bilateral relations to a new phase.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement followed Albar's meeting with Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with Iraqi senior officials including Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan, Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz and
Foreign Minister Mohammad Said Al-Sahaf, AlBar called on the U.N.
to "take serious and decisive efforts" to end the sanctions imposed
on Iraq since 1990.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the U.S. and Britain to abolish the two "
illegal and unjustifiable no-fly zones" in northern and southern
Iraq, set up after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
AlBar, heading an economic and trade delegation, arrived in the
Iraqi capital on Friday to attend the meetings of the Joint Iraqi-
Malaysian Trade And Economic Committee. The last round was held in
Baghdad in 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
