<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration Signatories Open FMs Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the signatories
of the Damascus Declaration met in Cairo Sunday night to discuss
regional issues and cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa opened the meeting, which
was also attended by his counterparts of the six members of the
Gulf Cooperation Council - Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi
Arabia and the United Arab Emirates - and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, originally scheduled for Monday and
Tuesday, will discuss issues related to the Arab world, especially
the Middle East peace process and ways to restore Arab solidarity,
reports here said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers would also review the items of the declaration and
its implementation.
</P>
<P>
The eight Arab countries signed the Damascus Declaration in
March 1991 following the Gulf War which ousted the Iraqi troops out
of Kuwait. The declaration called for cooperation in politics,
economy and regional security among the signatories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
