<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Turks Indicted in Jordan for Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Two Turkish nationals have been
indicted in Jordan for smuggling 107 kilograms of heroin and other
drugs into the kingdom, police sources here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two men, identified as Adnan Batch, a truck driver who is
now under detention in Jordan, and Ibrahim Oyar, who is at large,
were suspected of colluding with an international drug wing.
</P>
<P>
Adnan was caught at the Jaber check point on the Jordanian-
Syrian border on April 7, when Jordanian customs officers detected
107 kilograms of heroin and other drugs in a secret compartment on
his truck.
</P>
<P>
Street value of the drugs amounted to over half a million
Jordanian dinars (700,000 U.S. dollars). Further investigations are
under way as Adnan confessed that the drugs would be delivered to
an unnamed Jordanian dealer.
</P>
<P>
General Military Prosecutor Mamoun Khasawneh of the Jordanian
State Security Court has endorsed the indictment of the two Turkish
citizens, police said.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, the suspects might face death penalties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
