<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli General Security Service or Shin Bet,
has decided to tighten security around Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and government ministers amid recent reports that extreme right-
wing activists intend to harm Barak.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli daily Ha'aretz Sunday quoted sources as saying
that "among the extremist elements of the Judea and Samaria
settlers, there is once again talk of potential threat posed to
them because of the progress in talks with Palestinian (National)
Authority representatives."
</P>
<P>
They stressed, however, they have not received any concrete
information. (Israel-Security)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- "No progress has been made in the Final Status Talks
with Israel though negotiations are seriously going on",
Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) Executive Committee
Secretary General Abu Mazen said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He told Voice of Palestine Radio, "the talks were stalled for
three days and the two teams are consulting their respective
leaderships on the new developments in negotiations."
</P>
<P>
While calling upon Israeli government to stop its settlement
activities, the Palestinian official stressed the need that Israel
should return to pre-June-1967 Middle East war border lines and to
implement the U.N. Security Council Resolutions 194, 242,and 338.
(Palestine-Israel-Negotiations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Center Party Chairman, Tourism Minister
Amnon Lipkin-Shahak is to be appointed transport minister and
deputy prime minister in replacement of Yitzhak Mordechai who is to
stand trial on sex charges.
</P>
<P>
The Transport portfolio agreement was reached in a meeting
between Shahak and Prime Minister Ehud Barak in Tel Aviv on Friday,
reports here said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Barak confirmed that he has no intention on reneging on a
Center-One Israel coalition pact that assigns the Transportation
post to the Center Party's leading figure. (Israel-Transport
Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel and the Palestinians on Sunday discussed
interim issues such as the release of Palestinian prisoners,
Israel's troop redeployment in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and
security cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat and his Israeli
counterpart Oded Eran met here Sunday afternoon, but nothing has
been decided yet.  The Palestinian side had submitted a long list
of about 270 Palestinians slated to be released by Israel, and Eran
promised Erekat that the Israeli side will think over their release
in the future, sources close to the talks said. (Israel-
Palestinians-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday ordered
Israeli negotiators not to discuss the status of Jerusalem with
their Palestinian counterparts in any talks for the time being.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Barak stated that he has instructed the
negotiating teams not to hold any discussions on Jerusalem at this
stage," a statement issued after Sunday's weekly cabinet meeting
said.
</P>
<P>
"According to the Camp David and Oslo accords, the Palestinians
will be able to raise the issue in the discussions on the permanent
settlement," the statement added. (Israel-Palestinian-Jerusalem)
</P>
</TEXT>
