<HEADLINE> One in Ten Properties in UK Drops in Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) - One in ten properties in Britain has
fallen in value during the past two years, and in some areas more
than 20 percent has been wiped off house prices.
</P>
<P>
The figures produced by Experian, the information company,
highlight a stark contrast between perceptions of a national price
boom and the reality that the market is severely fragmented.
</P>
<P>
The research released Sunday shows that in 8 percent of postal
regions in England and Wales prices have dropped by up to 5
percent, and by up to 10 percent in 3 percent of regions.
</P>
<P>
The news follows figures from Nationwide building society that
show house prices fell by 0.4 percent in May compared with April.
However, experts say an outright crash is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bank of England, house prices have risen by 16
percent over the past year, but the Bank believes property
inflation will drop back to 10 percent in 2000 and 8 percent in
2001.
</P>
<P>
Some economists think the Bank will start cutting the base rate
later this year. Therefore, borrowers would be well advised not to
fix their mortgage rates now.
</P>
<P>
Bruno Rost from Experian said: "All markets have a nasty habit
of stampeding over cliffs. There are already signs that the
housing boom is coming to a swift end ..."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
