<DOCNO> XIE20000604.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Urges Lebanon to Restore Control of Southern Border Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Sunday urged Lebanon to restore its control in its southern border
area, which he said is a precondition for a French participation
in a future U.N. peacekeeping mission there.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone conversation with United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan, Chirac said that unless Lebanon promises to
send government troops there, France will not join an expanded U.N.
peacekeeping mission in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman of the Elysee presidential palace, Catherine
Colonna, quoted Chirac as saying that according to U.N. Security
Council Resolution 425, the mission of the United Nations Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) is to help Lebanese government restore
control in the territories occupied by Israel in 1978.
</P>
<P>
``Any deployment of U.N. has no other sense but to help Lebanon
restore its authority and (UNIFIL) is not for replacing Lebanon or
doing in its place what it should do,'' said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He said that the conditions presented by France for joining an
expanded UNIFIL mission, which includes deployment of Lebanese
government troops in the border area, have not been met.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's border area with Israel has been under the control of
the Hezbollah guerrillas after Israeli troops pulled out two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan has suggested
that the UNIFIL be expanded from the present 4,500 to 7,900 and be
re-deployed in Lebanon's southern border area.
</P>
<P>
France, which has 249 soldiers serving in UNIFIL since 1978,
has been asked to play a leading role in the future U.N. expanded
mission in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
