<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Clash with Police at Opening of OAS in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Protesters are accusing police "overacting" to their "peaceful
demonstration" against global corporate impact on environment and
human society.
</P>
<P>
Local television said that the peaceful demonstration turned
into an ugly scene when police "pepper sprayed and tear gassed"
the crowd of protesters, whose number is estimated at several
thousand around the city.
</P>
<P>
Up to 4,000 Canadian and U.S. police on both sides of the
Detroit River are being reported to gear up to ensure that Windsor
won't be made another scenario like that of Seattle or Washington
DC. in the past six months, when tens of thousands of protesters
clashed with police in similar confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of 34 member states have been invited to
attend the three-day 30th OAS General Assembly to be opened Sunday
until Tuesday. This is the first time such a meeting has ever been
held in Canada since the country joined the organization in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Among issues on the agenda are democracy, human rights, war-
affected children, corporate social responsibility, illicit trade
in drugs and other crimes, according to Canadian Foreign Minister
Lloyd Axworthy, who will chair what he described as "a Ministerial
Dialogue Session." 
</P>
</TEXT>
