<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cyprus Government in Dilemma on Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government is now in a
dilemma on the issue of fuel prices, due to the rejection of its
fuel hike bill by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Following a cabinet meeting on Wednesday, the Cyprus government
announced the decision to raise petrol price from 40 cents to 44
cents in Cyprus pound (from 64 cents to 70 cents in U.S. dollar) a
liter and diesel from 14.6 cents to 16.6 cents in pound (from 23.4
cents to 26.6 cents in dollar) a liter.
</P>
<P>
The decision came into effect immediately after the
announcement, but after 29 hours, the House of Representatives
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
Voting against the government bill were 24 deputies from the
left-wing AKEL party and the Democratic DIKO party, and 18 ruling
Democratic Rally party deputies favored the bill.
</P>
<P>
AKEL and DIKO considered the price hike as "unpopular", arguing
that crude oil prices were about to come down as the oil-producing
countries had just agreed to increase production.
</P>
<P>
President of the House of the Representatives Spyros Kyprianou
said that the 29-hour price hike was illegal.
</P>
<P>
However, government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou asserted that
there had been nothing illegal about the price rise.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Takis Clerides said that "for me at least the
House decision is incomprehensible."
</P>
<P>
The refusal of the House of Representatives to approve the bill
also made the island's oil importing companies angry, which
threatened not to bring in any more crude.
</P>
<P>
Commerce and Industry Minister Nicos Rolandis confirmed that the
oil companies had told him during an emergency meeting that they
would not buy "a single barrel more" of crude unless the prices
went up or subsidies continued.
</P>
<P>
According to local Sunday Mail newspaper, existing reserves of
oil on the island would last only until the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Now the government appears to have to carry on subsiding oil
imports, as it has been doing ever since the turn of the year, when
the price of crude hit the roof and the Cyprus pound began to
slide.
</P>
<P>
Crude prices have not come down significantly in the past five
months, and the value of the Cyprus pound against the dollar has
slid to 1.60 dollar one pound, from 1.80 dollar one pound at the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The subsidies to oil companies have already cost the state
coffers some 14 million pounds (22.4 million dollars) and would, if
continued, cost the state some 50 million pounds (80 million
dollars) by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
It is obviously an unbearable burden for the country's already
badly depleted public finances.
</P>
<P>
For the oil importing companies, the high price of crude oil and
the low value of the Cyprus pound against the U.S. dollar mean that
they would lose about 5 million pounds (8 million dollars) a month,
if there were no state subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus cabinet will hold a meeting on Wednesday to
reconsider the fuel price issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
