<HEADLINE> British Army Plays Down High Desertions: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- In response to newspaper reports
that a record proportion of soldiers had deserted or gone absent
without leave in 1999, the British Army on Sunday insisted that it
was a "caring employer".
</P>
<P>
"We think of ourselves as a caring employer, and commanding
officers are encouraged to be as compassionate as possible," a
Reuters report quoted "an army spokesman" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The remarks was made after The Observer reported Sunday that
one in 48 soldiers had gone missing in last year, mainly because
of bullying and abuse.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that while the proportion of soldiers
deserting was now the highest since the end of conscription, the
actual number was lower than in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"The basic position is there were roughly 2,000 soldiers
missing last year. That includes everyone from serious cases to
less serious cases of lateness -- when someone has just missed a
train," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the army had a zero-tolerance attitude
towards bullying and harassment and had put measures in place to
protect recruits, including a confidential support line.
</P>
<P>
Britain's army is under strain from a combination of regular
duties in Northern Ireland, Germany and Cyprus and high-profile
interventions in the Balkans and Sierra Leone, the Reuters report
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
