<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Sign Accords, Differences Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Russia and the
United States signed here Sunday a number of accords on strategic
stability and a joint center sharing information on missile
launches.
</P>
<P>
Both Russian President Vladimir Putin and his U.S. counterpart,
Bill Clinton, expressed satisfaction with their talks, but
differences remain on such issues as arms control and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The accords signed in the Kremlin include a joint statement on
strategic stability principles and a memorandum on the formation
of a joint center for exchanging information about missile
launches and reports from early warning systems.
</P>
<P>
According to the joint statement, the two leaders agreed to
intensify the dialogue on anti-ballistic missile issues and
further cuts in strategic forces in the framework of the proposed
START III treaty.
</P>
<P>
Russia is opposed to U.S. plans to build a national missile
defense system in violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
On strategic arms reduction, Moscow has proposed that each side
cut nuclear warheads to 1,500, but Washington is only prepared to
reduce the stockpile to 2,500 each.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement, the two presidents agreed that the ABM
treaty makes a significant contribution to the limitation of
strategic armaments and they confirmed their loyalty to the treaty
as a cornerstone of strategic stability.
</P>
<P>
They confirmed their adherence to the continuation of efforts
to strengthen the ABM treaty and make it more effective in the
future "given any changes in the international security sphere,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here Saturday on a three-day working visit to
Russia. He is scheduled to leave Monday for Ukraine, the last stop
of his Europe tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
