<HEADLINE> S. leone Rebels Offer Peace for Sankoh Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean rebels field commander
Issa Ceesay has reiterated a demand for the release of rebel
leader Foday Sankoh as a condition for peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcast Corporation (BBC) quoted him on Sunday as
speaking in one of its exclusive interviews that the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels now wanted to work with
the United Nations for peace.
</P>
<P>
The rebel general was making the appeal at a time when the UN
peacekeeping forces were making a push to re-occupy positions it
abandoned when the rebels attacked them in early May.
</P>
<P>
He said via phone from a rebel controled region in Sierra Leone
that Sankoh should be released to a neutral country such as Togo,
where the shattered Lome peace accord was signed in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
He also said Sankoh was the only man he would take orders from.
</P>
<P>
He also denied a UN announcement that the RUF attacked Indian
peacekeepers as they occupied the strategic crossroads at Rogberi
Junction.
</P>
<P>
The Indian contingent is now digging in defensively at Rogberi,
 85 kilomerters from the capital Freetown, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
The UN mission head in the West African nation Oluyemi Adeniji
had said that the international troops would, where necessary,
use force to retake more positions from rebel control.
</P>
<P>
He said the RUF would have to withdraw voluntarily to the
positions agreed in the Lome accord or be forced to do so.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a combination of diplomacy and force. We are
determined to enforce the Lome agreement," he said Sunday in the
country's capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
UN forces are now in striking distance of the town of Lunsar,
on the road to the eastern rebel stronghold of Makeni and the
diamond mines which have been the key cause of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Pro- government forces captured Lunsar on Monday but were
forced into a hasty withdrawal a day later.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh is currently held by the Sierra Leone Government in a
secret location and the government is believed to have prepared
criminal charges against him.
</P>
<P>
He was last under arrest in 1998, in the hands of the Nigeria
led West African peacekeeping force or Ecomog, but he was
released to participate in the peace accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
