<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major environment news stories Xinhua released last week:
</P>
<P>
 China Drafts Plan for Dust Storm Prevention
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology has drafted a plan for
prevention of dust storms and desertification in China to be
implemented in the following five years.
</P>
<P>
A ministry official said the plan will be executed starting
from 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, in the capital city of Beijing and
neighboring cities of Tianjin, Zhangjiakou and Chengde, more trees
and grass will be planted and high-efficient agriculture will be
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
China to Hold Book Fair for Environmental Protection
</P>
<P>
China will hold a large-scale book fair in 35 cities around
the country to mark the World Environment Day on June 5.
</P>
<P>
The cities include Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenyang,
Hangzhou, Jinan, Dalian, Qingdao, Changzhou and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 bookstores in these cities will participate in
the fair by putting on their shelves over 200 titles on
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Heavy Industrial Base Promotes Clean Production
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province, a heavy industrial center in northeast
China, is actively promoting clean production to check pollution.
</P>
<P>
Already involved in cleaning up their production are 200 local
enterprises in the heavy industrial cities of Shenyang, Anshan
and Fushun, according to a provincial official in charge of
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The province started to enforce clean production in 1995, when
the provincial bureau of environmental protection and the State
Economic and Trade Commission jointly launched a production
project characterized by low consumption, low pollution and high
return.
</P>
<P>
Afforestation Campaign Launched in Tibet
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region launched an afforestation drive
recently on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, China's
largest, to prevent the ecological environment there from further
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
The drive, mainly carried out in Qamdo Prefecture where Lancang,
Nujiang and Jinsha rivers meet, is expected to cost 590 million
yuan. It involves seven projects such as closing mountains off to
livestock grazing, planting trees and protecting virgin forests.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, China will invest 103.5 billion yuan to
save the natural forests along the upper reaches of the Yangtze
and Yellow rivers, covering 13 provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
