<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
South China's Guangdong Province will exert greater efforts to
improve the quality of water this year, Governor Lu Ruihua has
said.
</P>
<P>
The province will try to reduce industrial pollution by closing
down a number of oil refineries and cement plants, the official
said at a meeting on urban and rural construction.
</P>
<P>
Preferential policies and funds will be allocated to the
construction of urban sewage treatment plants, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Water Pollution in Major Rivers, Lakes Reduced
</P>
<P>
China has made headway in controlling water pollution in three
rivers and three lakes, which are most polluted, but more arduous
efforts are needed to achieve the pollution controlling targets
set for 2000.
</P>
<P>
Lu Xinyuan, Director of the Pollution Control Department of the
State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA), said that
pollution of the rivers of Huanhe, Liaohe and Haihe,and the lakes
of Taihu, Dianchi and Caohu has been greatly reduced and their
water quality improved. But major tributaries of the rivers and
sections of the lakes are still polluted.
</P>
<P>
HK Launches Trial of Clean Fuel Light Buses
</P>
<P>
 The trial of alternative fuel light buses was launched in
Hong Kong on Saturday as part of a key government initiative to
reduce air pollution from diesel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11 liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) light buses and
five electric light buses will take part in the six-month trial
starting operation on June 5, the World Environment Day.
</P>
<P>
The light buses will run on eight routes covering roads with
different conditions.
</P>
<P>
Lead Poisoning Among Shanghai Children Reduced
</P>
<P>
The rate of children who suffer lead poisoning in Shanghai has
been reduced from 37.8 percent in 1997 to 24.8 percent, according
to a research report released in Shanghai recently.
</P>
<P>
The two-year study, conducted by a group of experts from the
Shanghai No. 2 Medical University, tested 1,972 children aged one
to six.
</P>
<P>
The results indicate that the average content of lead in these
children's blood has been reduced to 76 micrograms from 83
micrograms per liter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China Tests Cellular Phones for Magnetic Radiation
</P>
<P>
Chinese industry authorities issued certificates today on
levels of magnetic radiation emitted from Motorola China and
Qingdao Haier cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that China conducted magnetic tests on
cellular phone products and issued certificates.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to limit the level of magnetic radiation
of electronic devices produced in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
