<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE's GDP Registers 10 Percent Increase in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates' gross
domestic product (GDP) rose by 10 percent in 1999 to reach 190
billion dirhams (51.9 billion U.S. dollars), according to a report
issued Sunday by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the rise to the increase in the revenues
of crude and manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil products contributed 147 billion dirhams (40.16 billion
dollars), or 74.4 percent of the GDP, whereas it contributed 137
billion dirhams (37.43 billion US dollars) or 79.2 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country's per capital income increased by 3.9 percent from
62,400 dirhams (17,049.18 dollars) in 1998 to 64,800 dirhams (17,
704.92 US dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The UAE also achieved a surplus in the total balance account for
5.6 billion dirhams (1.530 billion dollars) and a 6.4 billion
dirhams (1.75 billion US dollars) surplus in current account.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in trade balance surged from only 2 billion dirhams
(546.45 million dollars) in 1998 to 12.4 billion dirhams (3.3
billion dollars) in 1999 due to the increase in the dirham exchange
rate against currencies of all UAE's leading trade partners, except
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
