<HEADLINE> Negotiations on Fiji Crisis to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Fiji coup leader George Speight
said in Suva on Sunday night that his talks with military leader
Frank Bainimarama were going well.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press, he said the talks
were fruitful and a draft accord had been drawn up, and the fine
details of which would be discussed Monday, including the terms of
an amnesty for him and his gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Speight and six gunmen took former prime minister Mahendra
Chaudhry and his most cabinet members in the parliament house on
May 19 and now insists on the establishment of a civilian
government in which he and his men should play an influential role
while military leader Bainimarama said the army wanted a period of
three months from the release of the hostages until the chiefs met
so that law and order could be restored.
</P>
<P>
Speight announced Saturday that the talks collapsed because of
reneging by the military side.
</P>
<P>
The two sides resumed their talks on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Speight refused to say when the hostages could be released, but
stressed they were all in good conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
