<HEADLINE> S. Africa Should Improve Workers' Skills: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South African Trade and
Industry Minister Alec Erwin said on Sunday that his government
should improve the skills of its workers and produce better
products in order to compete on world markets.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the new 30 million rand (about 4.3 million
U.S. dollars) expansion of Kolosus Automotive Leather, Erwin said
the old South Africa, which was "protected from the world,
isolated from the world, trading only with ourselves", could not
continue.
</P>
<P>
Kolosus is one of South Africa's major producers of automotive
leather and the technologically advanced plant is designed to help
it expand its share of a very competitive world market.
</P>
<P>
"We had to begin trading with the whole world, making things
that compare to the best in the world. This has not been easily
done. It has meant many things have had to change," Erwin said.
</P>
<P>
"We have had to improve the skills of our workers, to produce
better quality products quickly for motor manufacturers in Europe
and the rest of the world," he added, emphasizing South Africa's
future lies in modern factories such as the Kolosus plant, which
is better skilled, better equipped and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
Erwin further pointed out that "the more investors and business
leaders and overseas investors can see modern factories here, the
more they will invest in South Africa." 
</P>
