<HEADLINE> S. African Democratic Party to Focus on Property Bill in Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The controversial draft
Property Bill and extending land rights to the homeless will be
the cornerstone of the South African opposition Democratic Party
local government elections, DP leader Tony Leon said in a
statement on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Leon said that Provincial and Local Government Minister Sydney
Mufamadi did not need the huge range of powers granted to him in
the bill to make regulations about rates.
</P>
<P>
He said the legislation would allow Mufamadi to control the
substance of the Act, without needing the approval of the
legislature or input from the public.
</P>
<P>
"Ratepayers are being kept in the dark about the content of
this legislation -- they literally do not know what they are
voting for in the local government elections," Leon said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the draft bill, the DP will campaign to outsource all
municipal services, offer incremental services, provide better
financial management and enforce rates and service charges more
strictly and equally.
</P>
<P>
Leon said municipal services, including refuse removal,
transport and water and sanitation, could be provided cheaper and
more effectively by private companies.
</P>
<P>
They would also offer "top-up" extra services for individual
households.
</P>
<P>
He said rent and service defaulters who could afford the fees
should be subject to criminal sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Local government elections are set to take place in November.
</P>
