<HEADLINE> Drought-Stricken NW China Bathed in Artificial Drizzle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Drought-stricken Yulin Prefecture, in
northern Shaanxi Province of northwestern China, is now soaking up
the light drizzle produced by an artificial rain operation.
</P>
<P>
Some 800,000 hectares of farmland have been affected by the
drought. The region received precipitation of less than 35 mm this
year, which was 60 percent less than normal.
</P>
<P>
The rain-making project has helped ease the situation by giving
5-25 mm of precipitation in the designated area.
</P>
<P>
Drought has plagued the prefecture for four years running. Over
one million people and 1.5 million livestock are suffering from a
drinking water shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
