<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Only about 10.8 percent of Jordanian families possess
computers, 17.4 percent of Jordanians use computers and over 75
percent of them have not received any training on computer
softwares or hardwares, said a national survey released on Sunday
by the Center of Strategic Studies of the prestigious University of
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey showed that internet users increased from
5.3 percent of the respondents in 1999 to 7.1 percent this year due
to the emergence of the mushrooming internet cafes across the
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that currently the kingdom has six
internet servers and some 20,000 internet users among the country's
4.5 million population.
</P>
<P>
Frequency of the use of internet was low with only 15 percent
getting online once a day, 50 percent once a week and 28 percent
once a month, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Iraq's oil output reached 3.1 million barrels per day
(bpd) at present and is expected to hit 3.3 million bpd by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's total oil exports by May 8th or 9th stood at about 2
million bpd in accordance with the 7th Phase of the U.N.-Iraq Oil-
for-Food program. The revenues from these exports will be nearly 8.
5 billion U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- United Arab Emirates (UAE)'s foreign trade in l999
made notable growth in spite of the unfavorable economic conditions
in regional markets, which were caused by the fluctuations in world
oil markets.
</P>
<P>
London-based Arabic daily Al-Haiyat on Sunday quoted a release
issued by UAE Industrial Bank as saying that UAE non-oil foreign
trade last year surged unprecedented 36 percent to 130.5 billion
dirhams (35.5 billion U.S dollars) from that in l998.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- General Manager of the Joint Jordan-Syria Free Trade
Zone (FTZ) Hasan Khairat said that the zone which officially opened
last Saturday have attracted 135 investors.
</P>
<P>
Arabic daily al-Alam al-Youm on Sunday reported that the joint
capital of the Jordan-Syria FTZ is about 60 million Syrian liras
(about 1.24 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
