<HEADLINE> Flood Hits Thailand's Eastern Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains over the past week have
caused flash flooding in Thailand's eastern provinces, the
official Thai News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Local residents in the eastern coastal province of Chanthaburi
were ordered to evacuate from the submerged areas, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Chanthaburi governor Praphan Chonweerawong had ordered hospital,
public-health centers and emergency medical units to be on alert,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The flood has also damaged roads in Sa Kaew province and the
coastal province of Trad, all in the eastern part of the country,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
There is no casualty reports so far.
</P>
<P>
The Thai meteorological department also warned of low-pressure
ridge and storms were expected in the Andaman Sea.
</P>
<P>
According to the Thai weather bureau, the flood is also
expected in other eastern provinces such as Prachin Buri, Ranong,
Phang-nga, Chumphon, Surat Thani and Nakhon Si Thammarat. 
</P>
