<HEADLINE> 5 Killed in Italy Train Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Five people were killed and another
one critically injured in a head-on collision early Sunday morning
between two cargo trains outside the station of Solignano, not far
from the Italian central northern city of Parma.
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred at 3:45 a.m. local time (1:45 GMT) when a 22-
carriage train traveling from Livorno to Bologna apparently
ignored a red light and plunged into a 13-carriage train, which
was on its way from Padua to La Spezia on the western coast of
Italy.
</P>
<P>
The two drivers of each train were all killed immediately and
the injured has been sent to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Italian Transport Minister Pierluigi Bersani, describing the
crash as a "real tragedy," said there appeared to be no technical
problems with the trains or the track which could have caused the
accident.
</P>
<P>
But Ezio Gallori, head of the train drivers' union Comu, said
that human error could not be blamed for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
This was the third crash on this stretch of track within eight
months, following the first one in October, 1999 which injured 20
people and the second on February 1 of this year, leaving four
drivers injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
