<HEADLINE> Shanghai Encourages Garbage Recycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A public awareness campaign was
held today here to encourage the recycling of plastic products,
buying of eco-friendly food and clothing, and protection of rivers.
</P>
<P>
Held to mark the World Environment Day tomorrow, the activities
were designed to enlighten Shanghai residents of the need for
environmental protection in their city, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
The city produces 13,000 tons of domestic wastes a day, and the
figure is increasing by eight percent every year.
</P>
<P>
Local residents are required to sort organic trash, such as
fruit peels, vegetables, and desert foods, inorganic trash such as
waste paper, glass, and metals, and pollutants like used batteries,
fluorescent lamps, and expired prescription medicine into
different bags, which are collected separately by sanitation
workers.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to extend the sorting of garbages to 1.5 million
dwellers, or over 10 percent of the city's population, this year.
</P>
<P>
The World Environment Day was established by the United Nations
in 1972. The theme set by UNEP for the year 2000 is "The
Environment Millennium - Time to Act."  
</P>
</TEXT>
