<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Holds Art Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- An art auction with dozens of works
of famous Chinese masters up for bids was held today in Lhasa,
capital of Tibet Autonomous Region, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
About 300 art lovers in Tibet took part in the auction, and
over 70 percent of the 270 works were sold.
</P>
<P>
Lobsang Dainpa, Tibet's first state-level auctioneer, said that
auctions are just beginning to catch the interest of Tibetans, and
artworks, especially paintings and calligraphy, are the most
popular items to go up on the auctioneer's block.
</P>
<P>
Lobsang Dainpa is also the manager of Tibet Xueyuan Auction
Company, the first of its kind in Tibet, established in November
1999. He said that Tibet has only two state-level auctioneers and
two auction companies, but he believes auctions have a bright
future.
</P>
<P>
"We have introduced artwork into the region by means of
auctions -- the next step is to introduce our art to outsiders,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
More auctions will be held elsewhere in Tibet in the next few
days, including the prefectures of Nyingchi and Xigaze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
