<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate President Urged to Resign by His Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Deputy Senate President,
Alhaji Abubakar has urged the Senate President Chuba Okadigbo to
resign immediately, accusing the top legislator of a demonstrated
lack of personal integrity in recent events.
</P>
<P>
He also said Saturday in his Abuja home that the senate will
re- convene on Monday, as against the will of the senate president
to adjourn the legislature's session until July 7, reported
Nigerian newspapers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said Okadigbo's removal of the two maces in the
senate's chamber, will not prevent the senate from re-convening,
for the senate was to make two new ones.
</P>
<P>
The police, claiming to be acting on the request of some
senators, stormed Okadigbo's Abuja residence Friday, but failed
to retrieve the removed maces.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the senate president told the police
he had sent the maces, symbol of the senate power, to his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo, when challenged on the event, said
the police's act is a clear breath of the immunity enjoyed by the
country's top legislators. But Obasanjo didn't comment on the
raging dispute between the president and vice president of the
senate.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also said by such acts as removal of maces to stop the
senate from debating on bills of vital importance and urgency for
his country, Okadigbo had demonstrated "an amazing lack of
self-control and complete lack of legitimacy and support from
senators".
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Okadigbo, who is the third most powerful
politician in Nigeria after the president and vice president,
insisted that he was the legitimate custodian of the maces and
has the power to adjourn the senate.
</P>
<P>
He described Friday's drama of forcing into his home by the
police as clear example of "executive lawlessness".
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo has repeatedly criticized the senate for
being responsible for the constant delays in passing important
bills, such as the anti-corruption bill or the 2000 federal
budget into laws.
</P>
<P>
The senators on the other hand accuse President Obasanjo of
acting unilaterally in issues that require the approval of the
senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
