<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White Farmers Criticize Government for Farm Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Commercial Farmers Union
(CFU) has described as a slap in the face of donors last week's
preliminary notice by the government to compulsorily acquire 804
farms for resettlement.
</P>
<P>
CFU Vice-President Collin Cloete said it was unfortunate that
the government decided to go ahead with the resettlement when
various donors were making submissions to assist in the
resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
"We will make our position clear this week when we have
explored all the legal aspects," said Cloete, adding that the
farmers feared further invasions, a situation that could disrupt
winter cropping.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe's government, buoyed by unequivocal
support from fellow Southern African Development Community
governments, decided to go ahead and take the farms without
compensation, much to the displeasure of western powers,
particularly former colonial master Britain.
</P>
<P>
The government has asked owners of the 804 farms until July 2
to file objections but this will not mean their land will not be
taken as this would mean the thousands of war veterans and
villagers occupying some 1,500 farms in protest to a slow
resettlement program, will merely dig in.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP, which had reversed its stance to stall land aid in
the spirit of the land conference it co-hosted with the
Zimbabwean government in 1998, seems to have reverted to it
following the gazetting of farms the government intends to take.
</P>
<P>
According to the British Broadcasting Corporation, a special
representative of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who had
initiated the offer for the UNDP to put together a financial
package to fund the land reforms, Mark Malloch-Brown had called
off his trip to Harare in apparent protest at the designation of
804 farms.
</P>
<P>
This has raised questions as to whether UNDP is genuinely
concerned with equitable land redistribution in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cloete said some of the listed farms belong to
tobacco farmers and this would affect deliveries of the crop to
the auction floors.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco sales were expected to bring in more than 300 million
U.S. dollars of the much needed foreign currency which has been
short for months now and has caused serious economic problems
like fuel shortages.
</P>
<P>
On the ability of farmers to finance their 100 million U.S.
dollars losses to farm invasion, Cloete said banks indicated they
would consider individual cases and act accordingly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
