<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Izmir International Fair, the oldest fair in Turkey
and one of the World's greatest, is making a face-lift and will
open its doors to visitors for the 69th time in August 2000 with a
new vision, reported Turkish Daily News on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The management of the Izmir Fair Services, Culture and Arts Inc.
has already started its preparations for this year's fair. Its
Izmir Great Culture Park project aims to change all aspects of the
fairground and reconstruct all its buildings, gathering them in one
single area and leaving the rest of the area green.
</P>
<P>
Izmir International Fair, which is also the only Turkish fair
that is a member of the International Fair Union, is not just a
trade fair, but also features cultural and arts activities.
</P>
<P>
The fair plans to attract more people than last year's 4
million.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Japan has agreed to grant Egypt a total of 45 million
U.S. dollars under three agreements signed between the two
countries in Cairo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Part of the grant is for the construction of a suspension bridge
across the Suez Canal, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The rest will be used to finance the revampment of a barrage in
the southern governorate of Fayyoum and the improvement of wheat
production in the governorates of Mersa Matruh and New Valley.
</P>
<P>
Japan has provided Egypt with around 10 billion dollars in grant
since 1982, according to the Japanese Embassy in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The inflation figures of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) has been forecasted to rise to an average of 5 percent over
the next two years as imports continue to increase from East Asia
where rising currency rates could translate to higher prices here,
reported Dubai based daily "Gulf News" Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts made by the Economist Intelligence Unit (EIU), a
private economic think-tank based in Britain, indicate that the
economic turnaround is expected to result in inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
The report said the UAE Ministry of Planning expects this year's
inflation at 2.5 percent, slightly up from last year's 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman plans to build a 420 million US dollars
tourist project as part of efforts to diversify its economy away
from energy revenues, reported the Dubai based daily "Gulf News"
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Al Sinani, director of planning at the Commerce and
Industry Ministry, said the project will include a golf course, 300
chalets and sea sports facilities along a 34-kilometre strip of
coast.
</P>
<P>
He said construction in the northern coastal area of Al-Sawadi
will start in 2001 and be completed in 2004.  
</P>
</TEXT>
