<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC To Discus Qatar pro-Iraq Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has raised a proposal on easing
the 10-year-long international embargo on Iraq during a meeting of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) held in Jeddah Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
GCC foreign ministers voiced welcome of the proposal and any
initiatives intended to lessen the suffering of the Iraqi people
under the U.N.-imposed sanctions since Iraqi invasion of
neighboring Kuwait in l990.
</P>
<P>
The details of the Qatari proposal are to be sent to the GCC
member states for appraisal.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of preserving Iraq's independence,
territorial integrity and sovereignty, the GCC foreign ministers,
however, said Iraq should comply with all U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, Qatar Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin al-Thani called
in Kuwait for a regional initiative to lift the sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process and the Israeli withdrawal from
South Lebanon, the GCC foreign ministers said the process stumbled
after Israel failed to comply with the signed agreements,
expressing hope that Lebanon's sovereignty and independence should
be respected.
</P>
<P>
They cautioned that Israel should not make its northern border
security a pretext to launch offensives against Lebanese people,
urging that just and permanent peace should be established soon.
</P>
<P>
On the relations with Iran, they expressed the GCC countries'
keenness on better ties with the country based on the principles of
good neighborliness, mutual respect, non-interference in each
other's internal affairs and resolving disputes through peaceful
means.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed hopes that Tehran can co-operate with the
GCC's Tripartite Commission on the Disputed Islands Issue between
United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Iran for a peaceful settlement of
that territorial stand-off .
</P>
<P>
The three Gulf-based islands of Abu Mousa, Greater and Lesser
Tunbs lie close to the strategic Hormuz Strait. They have been
under Iran's control since l971 but are also claimed by UAE which
called for international arbitration in the Hague. Iran rejected
the notion, holding that the disputed islands are its national
territories.
</P>
<P>
GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, UAE, Qatar and Oman.
</P>
</TEXT>
