<HEADLINE> Yemeni President Leaves For Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni president Ali Abdullah Saleh
left here Sunday morning for a state visit to Germany.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to discuss the bilateral relations between Yemen
and Germany and the ways to further develop them with German
Chancellor Jerhard Schroeder and top German officials.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the Yemeni and German leaders will also focus
on the developments of the Middle East peace process, the situation
in the Horn of Africa region in light of the peaceful efforts being
made to stop the raging border fighting between Ethiopia and
Eritrea and the endeavors of achieving national reconciliation in
Somalia, the local daily Al-Thawra reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Abdul-Qader Ba-Jammal as saying that "the visit is specially
important because Germany is one of the main development partners,"
expressing hope that it can attract more German investment into
Yemen.
</P>
<P>
It will provide a significant opportunity to acquaint German
business people with the successful administrative and financial
reforms Yemen achieved over the past five years, he added.
</P>
<P>
The joint co-ordination between both countries is going on well
not just because Germany is one of Yemen's principal aid donors,
but also because it enjoys strong presence within the European
group which will further enhance the Yemen-EU partnership, Ba-Gamal
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Saleh will inaugurate the Yemeni pavilion at
the Expo 2000 World Exhibition which opened in Hanover on Thursday.
</P>
