<HEADLINE> No Progress in Final Status Talks: Palestinian Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- "No progress has been made in the Final
Status Talks with Israel though negotiations are seriously going
on", Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) Executive Committee
Secretary General Abu Mazen said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He told Voice of Palestine Radio, "the talks were stalled for
three days and the two teams are consulting their respective
leaderships on the new developments in negotiations."
</P>
<P>
While calling upon Israeli government to stop its settlement
activities, the Palestinian official stressed the need that Israel
should return to pre-June-1967 Middle East war border lines and to
implement the U.N. Security Council Resolutions 194, 242,and 338.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian Council (PLC) Speaker and Chief
Palestinian Negotiator to the Final Status talks, Ahmed Qurei,
clarified that there still were a wide gab between both sides
specially on the major issues in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli stand on issues of Jerusalem and refugees was still
far from international resolutions and the principle of the peace
process, Qurei pointed out stressing that Jerusalem would be the
capital of the planned Palestinian state and that U.N. Security
Council Resolution 194 was the sole way for resolving the refugees
issue.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian delegation rejected an Israeli proposal to
discuss the security matters, he said that such subject should not
be handled before demarcating the borders between Israel and the
would-be Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
He denied as "baseless" the London-based Arabic-daily Al-
Haiyat's report about a breakthrough in the final status talks
between the Palestinian and Israeli teams.
</P>
<P>
PLO Executive Committee in a statement on Saturday night said "
all previous rounds of talks came to a dead end as the Israeli side
failed to comply with the signed agreements or resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Council is to meet on June 28 and 29 to
discuss the date of declaration of the Palestinian statehood.
</P>
</TEXT>
