<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- An agreement is expected soon on the border demarcation
between Israel and Lebanon, which will pave the way for the United
Nations to verify Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon to the
internationally recognized boundary.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Middle East special envoy Terje Larsen arrived here
Saturday night to brief Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on his
talks with Lebanese leaders over the border issue. The meeting is
expected to take place at the prime minister's home, Barak's
spokesman Gadi Baltiansky said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. cartographers have been marking the border in cooperation
with Lebanese and Israeli officials. Lebanese Prime Minister Salim
Hoss said Saturday Lebanon is close to agreement with the U.N. on
the matter, with the exception of three places between Rumeish
village and Israel's Metulla.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's Center Party Chairman and Tourism Minister Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak is to be appointed transport minister and deputy
prime minister to replace former Center leader Yitzhak Mordechai,
who resigned from the government after the attorney-general
endorsed his indictment on counts of indecent assault and sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
The transport portfolio agreement was reached in a meeting
between Shahak and Prime Minister Barak in Tel Aviv on Friday.
Barak affirmed that he has no intention on reneging on a Center-One
Israel coalition pact, which assigns the Transportation Ministry to
the Center's leading figure.
</P>
<P>
Shahak's re-assignment will be delayed for a few days, while
Barak negotiates with the Center Party's new number two, Knesset
(Parliament) member Dan Meridor, about the tourism portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Barak said Friday that Israel should see an agreement with
the Palestinians in which 80 percent of settlers remain under
Israeli sovereignty as an historical achievement.
</P>
<P>
Barak, speaking at a meeting of his Labor Party's central
command on Friday, which was convened to elect a candidate for the
presidency, addressed recent criticisms leveled against him,
including by Interior Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
He said:" If we reach a situation whereby, either under a
framework agreement or permanent status accord, 80 percent or more
of the settlers in Judea and Samaria (the West Bank) remain in an
area recognized by the rest of the world as solely Israel's, under
Israeli sovereignty, we will have accomplished an historic and
unique achievement."
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian anti-terrorist troops rescued Adi Sharon, a 12-year-
old Israeli, on Thursday night, following a ten-month captivity at
the hands of kidnappers demanding millions of U.S. dollars in
ransom.
</P>
<P>
The boy was found in a basement in the two of Penza, some 560
kilometers southeast of Moscow. Adi is recovering in a Moscow
hospital from his order, which involved the severing of two of his
fingers, and is expected to arrive in Israel with his father next
week.
</P>
<P>
Barak expressed his gratitude on Saturday to Russian President
Vladimir Putin for the freeing of the boy. According to Russian
news agencies, the 13 gang members responsible for the kidnapping
were arrested. 
</P>
