<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharak to Be Named Israeli Transport Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Center Party Chairman,
Tourism Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak is to be appointed transport
minister and deputy prime minister in replacement of Yitzhak
Mordechai who is to stand trial on sex charges.
</P>
<P>
The Transport portfolio agreement was reached in a meeting
between Shahak and Prime Minister Ehud Barak in Tel Aviv on Friday,
reports here said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Barak confirmed that he has no intention on reneging on a
Center-One Israel coalition pact that assigns the Transportation
post to the Center Party's leading figure.
</P>
<P>
Shahak's reassignment will be put off for a few days as Barak
has to negotiate with the Center's Party's new number two man,
Knesset (parliament) Member Dan Meridor, about the tourism
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Meridor have discussed this portfolio twice with no
results yielded. Meridor, chairman of the Knesset Foreign Affairs
and Defense Committee, has reservations about the assignment as he
sets his sight on other posts such as the Justice Ministry
portfolio now held by Yossi Beilin (One Israel). Meridor is also
said to be interested in receiving the Defense portfolio, now held
by Barak.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Barak may use the opportunity of
Mordechai's resignation to reshuffle the cabinet in view of Housing
Minister Yitzhak Levy's intention to quit the government over the
handover of the Arab village Abu Dis just outside Jerusalem to full
Palestinian control. Levy is from the five-member National
Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
Another vacancy in the cabinet is also likely to be created as
Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres is the leading candidate
for president.
</P>
<P>
Barak's aid have indicated that the prime minister is eager for
Meridor to take the Tourism offer, and that he plans to assign
Meridor, a close friend of Barak, to the ministerial team
responsible for advanced stages of negotiations with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In case Meridor turned down the Tourism portfolio proposal, the
same offer will be put to the Center's next highest-ranking figure,
Knesset Member Ronim Milo.
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, the ex-transport minister Mordechai has
appealed for a one-month postponement of the Knesset House
Committee hearing, which is due to convene on Monday to decide
whether to strip him of immunity.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein, who has called for
stripping Mordechai of immunity as Knesset Member to pave the way
for him to be put on trial, is expected to reply to Mordechai's
request on Sunday. The former Center chairman has already received
a one-week delay to consider whether to attend the hearing.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, retired general at the age of 55, submitted his
resignation at the end of May in the face of charges that he
sexually assaulted three women over the past eight years. If
convicted, he could face up to seven years in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
