<P>
The two presidents opened talks at around 1:15 p.m. (0915 GMT)
with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, Washington's
expert on Russian affairs, and Putin's chief foreign policy aide,
Sergei Prikhodko present, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived Saturday and had an informal Kremlin dinner
with Putin during which they got down to business, discussing
nuclear arms, the Balkans and the Caucasus, Russian officials here
said.
</P>
<P>
The discussions would last all afternoon, and be joined later
by ministers of both countries.
</P>
<P>
The main focus of the talks would be U.S. plans for a national
missile defense (NMD) system which Washington insists it needs to
protect the United States from so-called "rogue states" like Iraq
and iran. But it is firmly opposed by Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
