<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Sets to Normalize Ties with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry
Undersecretary Faruk Logoglu is scheduled to pay an official visit
to Iraq between June 4-7 to smooth the way for better relations
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The senior foreign ministry official's visit is taking place at
a time when Iraq has accused Turkey of providing air bases for U.S.
and British warplanes which have recently intensified their strikes
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Logoglu is expected to touch on all the
bilateral and regional issues with his host Nuri Ismail Al-Weis,
senior undersecretary of the Iraqi Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
But the two men would most possibly focus their discussions on
the so-called Operation Northern Watch by the U.S. and Britain, a
major issue plaguing the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a Baghdad report, Iraqi Foreign Minister Muhammad
Al-Sahaf has blamed Turkey for allowing the United States and Great
Britain to use its territory to launch air strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahaf sent a letter to the secretary-general of the Arab
League, Esmat Abdel Meguid, complaining about increased bombings
against his country and Turkey's role in the operations, asking the
Arab League to condemn the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
He stated that Iraq has been reserving its right to claim
compensations form Turkey, the United States and the united
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Iraq's accusations over Turkey's involvement in the
latest bombings, Turkish diplomatic sources have contended that
Turkey played no role in the bombings, reported Turkish Daily News.
</P>
<P>
NATO member Turkey, which strongly supported U.S.-led forces
during the Gulf War to end Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, ironically
suffered an enormous loss of some 40 billion U.S. dollars in
potential revenues over the subsequent decade, as a result of the
U.S.-supported U.N. embargo on trade with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been known to stand for the sanctions lifted so that
lucrative trade with Iraq will be fully restored.
</P>
<P>
However, the strategic partnership forged between Ankara and
Washington has restricted Turkey's field of maneuverability because
of U.S. demand to punish President Saddam Hussein of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the restrictions, Turkey believes, there is still
room to expand trade volumes between Turkey and Iraq under the U.N.
food for oil program which enables Iraq to import 5 billion dollars
worth of foodstuffs and drugs annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
