<HEADLINE> mee060402hke-- Security for Israeli PM Enhanced Following Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli General Security
Service or Shin Bet, has decided to tighten security around Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and government ministers amid recent reports
that extreme right-wing activists intend to harm Barak.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli daily Ha'aretz Sunday quoted sources as saying
that "among the extremist elements of the Judea and Samaria
settlers, there is once again talk of potential threat posed to
them because of the progress in talks with Palestinian (National)
Authority representatives."
</P>
<P>
They stressed, however, they have not received any concrete
information.
</P>
<P>
The extremists are also considering contacting rabbis who will
be willing to provide the settlements with a "spiritual umbrella"
backed up with rulings from Jewish religious law.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post, another Israeli daily, reported on Sunday
that there has been a sharp rise in recent weeks in the number of
threats against Barak by right-wing elements, reaching proportions
prior to the assassination of late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Former Shin Bet head Carmi Gillion called on authorities to
arrest all rabbis whose statements made in recent days can be
perceived as incitement.
</P>
<P>
The Shin Bet decided, following consultations with the police's
intelligence unit, to try and draft more agents among settlers, to
increase surveillance over extremist groups and to meet with rabbis
and settler leaders in an attempt to communicate the severity of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the Labor Party's Central Committee on Friday that
Israel will keep 80 percent of settlers on the West Bank (or Judea
and Samaria as the Israelis term it) under Israeli sovereignty in a
possible upcoming agreement with the Palestinians. He said such an
agreement should be seen as a historic achievement.
</P>
<P>
The future of Israeli settlements is one of the tough issues to
be solved in the final status negotiations between Israelis and
Palestinians, who aim to clinch a permanent accord by September 13.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have reportedly reached
agreements after nine rounds of talks in Stockholm including the
fate of Jerusalem and the arrangements of refugees.
</P>
<P>
To help both sides bridge their remaining gaps, foreign
statesmen and diplomats will arrive in the region this week to
mediate the Israeli-Palestinian track of peace process.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson will arrive in Israel on
Sunday and meet Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross will land in Israel on Monday while
U.S. State of Secretary Madeleine Albright will arrive on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
