<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets with German Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
Sunday with German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Fischer were expected to discuss regional issues,
including the Middle East peace process and the Euro-Mediterranean
cooperation, and ways of promoting bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Fischer arrived in Cairo on Saturday for a two-day visit. He
held talks late Saturday with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa,
who told reporters after the meeting that they tackled the Mideast
peace process and issues in the Mediterranean region.
</P>
<P>
Fischer stressed at the press conference that realization of
peace in the Middle East is a prerequisite for stability in the
Mediterranean region. Germany has been stepping up efforts with its
partners to help push forward the Mideast peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed troop withdrawal from south Lebanon on May 24,
ending its 22-year occupation of a border strip in the region.
Syria and Israel have yet to resume talks on the return of the
Golan Heights that Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast
War. The Palestinians and Israel are negotiating for a final peace
accord, with little progress.
</P>
<P>
Germany, along with the European Union's other members and the
15-nation bloc itself, wants to play a major part in helping seek
peaceful settlement of the half-century Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said his talks with Fischer also took up the bilateral
ties, especially means of increasing German investments in Egypt
and ways to promote trade.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Egypt's largest trading partner among the EU members
and the second largest aid donor after the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
