<HEADLINE> Presidents of Congo, Rwanda Agree to Restore Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) and Rwanda have agreed to resume
bilateral relations after secret talks in the Kenyan city of
Eldoret on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time of such talks since Rwanda sent troops
into DRC to back a rebellion there 22 months ago.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued after the meeting, Rwandan
President Paul Kagame and his counterpart Laurent Kabila also
resolved to work together to promote peace, security and
stability in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the meeting said this was the first step toward
efforts to restore relations between Rwanda and the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, which helped Kabila to oust Mobutu Sese Seko in 1997,
later fell out with the Congolese president.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, brokered by Kenyan president Daniel arap Moi, took
people by surprise as it had not been announced in advance.
