<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Urged to Conserve Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyans are urged to conserve
electricity by using alternative energy for cooking and water
heating, and to switch off all lights not in use.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Power and Lighting Company Saturday issued a
statement, appealing to all electricity consumers to use the
little available prudently for the water in the dams to last
through the dry period, the Sunday Nation newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
The company asked customers in business zones to turn off neon
signs and decorative and exterior lights that do not serve any
security purpose.
</P>
<P>
Industrial customers are also requested to ensure their
equipment and machinery are switched off when not in use and that
they are maintained in good conditions to enhance efficiency in
electricity consumption.
</P>
<P>
Due to a two-year drought leading to the lowest water levels of
major energy reservoirs which have affected the power generation,
Kenya faces an electricity shortfall of between 154 and 360
megawatt in the off-peak and peak hours respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government a week ago introduced a 12-hour power
rationing schedule starting this week, with industrial and
commercial consumers having power between 6:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.
everyday except Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to power rationing, the government is also taking
other measures to solve the power shortage including the
importing of more electricity from Uganda and the recent signing
of two agreements to accelerate the delivery of two 55-megawatt
diesel generating plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
