<HEADLINE> Drug trafficking Increasing in East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Wealthy foreign drug barons are
increasingly using Ugandans as couriers to smuggle narcotics and
other illicit drugs out of East Africa, the New Vision reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The drug lords, who operate an organized network, ferry the
drugs from Asian countries through East Africa to America and
Europe, said Erasmus Opio, acting director of the Crimes
Investigation Department.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of illicit dealing in drugs is rising in the region.
We are concerned that it is well organized and involves a number
of people, mainly foreign nationals," Opio was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Opio said East Africa is increasingly becoming a drug transit
hub. "Originally, we were only involved in the consumption. But as
time passed, we have noted that there are also production centers
of drugs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Drug crimes are a new phenomenon in the region, caused by
globalization and easy communication, said Opio, stressing that
the threat demands specialized personnel to handle it.
</P>
<P>
East African countries recently agreed to intensify operations
at their common borders to fight drug trafficking, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
