<HEADLINE> Pakistan Recovers 3.7 Billion Dollars from Loan Defaulters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The current government of
Pakistan has made a significant progress in accountability, a
local report said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 19.39 billion rupees (3.7 million U.S. dollars) had
been recovered by the National Accountability Bureau (NAB) from
loan defaulters and corrupt people, Pakistan Observer, a daily
newspaper, said quoting official sources.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be one of the major achievements of the
current government which has, soon after its inception last
October, announced accountability as its imperative task as a way
to eliminate corruption and increase revenue.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released here, altogether the NAB
arrested 122 people on corruption and criminal charges out of
which 24 are still in custody, 47 in judicial lock-up while 24
accused absconding.
</P>
<P>
The government has also converted non-performing loans of 30
billion rupees (5.6 billion dollars) into performing ones through
various measures, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
