<HEADLINE> Zanzibar to Increase Budget by 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government is
expected to increase its budget by 20 percent in the next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian official Sunday News quoted the Zanzibar Minister
for Finance Amina Salum Ali as saying during a pre-budget briefing
on Saturday that the government is about to spend 75.6 billion
Tanzanian shillings (about 94.5 million U.S. dollars) during the
2000/2001 fiscal year beginning on July 1, an increase of 12.9
billion (about 16.1 million U.S. dollars) compared with the
current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The minister said 53.6 billion shillings (about 67 million U.S.
dollars) out of the estimates will be for recurrent activities and
the balance will be allocated for development votes.
</P>
<P>
However, Amina explained, in the next development plan, the
government will implement a total of 33 projects down from 39
planned for the current financial year.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, under the new budget proposals, the
government will place emphasis on implementing self-help projects
and will continue to execute vigorous revenue collection drive to
enable them to meet their recurrent and development requirements.
</P>
<P>
The Isles budget session will open in Zanzibar next Thursday
when the Minister of State Ali Juma Shamuhuna will present the
annual development plan while Minister Amina will table the budget
proposals, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar is a semi-autonomous state on the Indian Ocean with
its own government and parliament in the United Republic of
Tanzania which was formed in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The economy in Zanzibar is developing slowly in recent years,
partly because of the sanctions imposed by the 15 European Union
nations to withhold their aid to the Isles due to the political
situation surfaced shortly after the 1995 general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
