<DOCNO> XIE20000604.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No One Injured in Manila Airport Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Authorities of the Ninoy Aquino
International Airport (NAIA) in Manila said Sunday that no one was
injured in a bomb blast at the airport earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Airport General Manager Antonio Gana said that the explosion
took place at the 10 meter-man-made embankment between the ramp
arrival curb site and the extension greeter's lounge.
</P>
<P>
"There was no security breach because this is a public place,"
Gana said.
</P>
<P>
A suspect for the bombing is a male between 24 and 29 years old
and the police has released a cartographic sketch of the suspect,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Gana said that two persons who were very close to the vicinity,
where the blast occurred are now being held for questioning by
airport authorities.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are still examining the explosive device used in
the blast, he said.
</P>
<P>
The manager said that immediately after the blast, a speeding
Ford Fiera was seen beating the red light between the Ninoy Aquino
Road and MIA road, nearing hitting a passenger bus.
</P>
<P>
Two passengers of the bus are now being questioned by airport
authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gana said that the two passengers may be able to give a lead as
to the plate number of the speeding van.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the authorities arrested 26 suspects for a spate of
bombings in the Philippine capital. The government blamed Muslim
rebels for the bombing incidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
