</P>
<P>
-- Pakistan's talks with the International Monetary Fund are
likely to continue after the budget, which is due on June 17, as
the pre-budget phase of negotiation concluded here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Nation:
</P>
<P>
-- To appease the protesting traders, the Ministry of Finance
has decided, in principle, to restructure the tax assessment
system of the Central Board of Revenue while the traders have
dropped their guns against the documentation of the economy on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Frontier Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Pakistan has 25 nuclear warheads, a recent Washington Times
report has said, quoting the Central Intelligence Agency and other
instititutions.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Observer:
</P>
<P>
-- Contrary to the widespread allegations of being slow and
soft, the National Accountability Bureau has made a significant
progress in the process of accountability till May 31, 2000 with
over 19 billion rupees (360 million U.S. dollars) from loan
defaulters and corrupt people recovered. 
</P>
