<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Makes Significant Diplomatic Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has made
two significant diplomatic changes with effect from the middle of
this month, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
They said Mangala Moonesinghe, the longest serving high
commissioner (ambassador) under the government of President
Chandrika Kumaratunga, moves to London from New Delhi while close
relative of the president Senaka Bandaranayake moves to New Delhi
from Paris.
</P>
<P>
Both Moonesinghe and Bandaranayake are considered as
confidantes of President Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believed much is expected from the two diplomats
in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Moonesinghe who commands respect from both the government and
the opposition circles has worked tirelessly to bring both India
and Sri Lanka closer in the recent times.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure, the Indo-Lanka relationship is at the
highest point and President Kumaratunga made two visits to India.
On a much publicized visit at the end of 1998, Sri Lanka signed a
bilateral free trade pact with India.
</P>
<P>
Moonesinghe is a devout Buddhist and a grandson of the late
Anagarika Dharmapala, a national hero and founder of India's
Mahabodi Society.
</P>
<P>
He takes over in London at a time when the Sri Lankan
government is seeking the support of the western nations including
Norway to play the role of peace brokers to help ending the 17-
year-old civil war with Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
Bandaranayake, an archeologist by profession, earlier this year
contested for the post of secretary general of the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government led a much unsuccessful campaign to
get him elected to the position. Only China and India voted in
his favor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
