<HEADLINE> Chinese Listed Dotcom Firms Post Better Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Both NASDAQ-listed Chinese dotcom
companies, the first Chinadotcom and then the Sina.com, reported
better than expected results in the first quarter despite concerns
about their profitability.
</P>
<P>
Chinadotcom Corporation reported total revenues of 20 million U.
S. dollars for the first quarter ending March 31 with a total loss
of 11 million U.S. dollars. The Sina.com reported 3.6 million U.S.
dollars in revenues with a total loss of 12.1 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although both companies are losing money from daily operations,
Chinadotcom reported a net profit of 109 million because of the
listing of Hongkong.com, a subsidiary of Chinadotcom.
</P>
<P>
Chinadotcom has four portals now in the Asia-Pacific region:
http://www.china.com, http://www.hongkong.com, http://www.taiwan.
com and http://www.cww.com.
</P>
<P>
As to the Sina.com, it would have reported a red-figure result
if without the help of a non-operating gain in the period. Wang
Zhidong, CEO of the Sina.com, said that they were excited about
the results as a public company.
</P>
<P>
Sina.com had 5 million registered users by the end of April and
reported 24 million daily surfers. Chinadotcom had attained 4.5
million registered users by the end of March with 16 million daily
surfers by April.
</P>
<P>
However, Peter Yip, CEO of Chinadotcom, said the number of
surfers was important, but it was unstable and changed every day,
their goal is " to improve the value to shareholders".
</P>
<P>
"We will turn to black next year," said Yip, " E-business
solutions and on-line advertising will be major revenue pools."
Revenues from the E-business accounted for 51 percent of
Chinadotcom's total income.
</P>
<P>
Sina is now dedicating resources to the development of Internet
software and WAP (wireless application protocol) techniques.
</P>
<P>
Sina.com launched its new Sina 2000 product recently and WAP
alliances with leading telecommunications vendors, such as
Ericsson, Motorola and Siemens to deliver content to wireless
devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
