<HEADLINE> Children's Day: Big Day for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Businesses that serve children's
interests were delighted to see their turnover rocket on the
International Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
Beijing department store staff said the sales volume of
children's items, including clothes, toys and food, increased by
200 percent last week compared to ordinary sales patterns.
</P>
<P>
Rough estimates indicate Chinese parents spent several billion
yuan on their children last week. And official statistics suggest
the one-fifth to one-third of an urban family's spending is for
children.
</P>
<P>
Hu Chao said," The market could be as large as several billion
U.S. dollars." Hu is manager of leyou.com, China's largest on-
line shop for children's things launched at the beginning of this
year.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 400 million people under 18 years old, 200
million under 14 and 20 million new-borns every year, China has a
huge market for children's items, she said.
</P>
<P>
Take children's clothes for example. An investigation by the
State Information Center on 37 Beijing-based department stores
show that total sales of children's clothes was 18.24 million yuan
( about 2.2 million U.S. dollars) last year, up 12.8 percent from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
With the implementation of the family planning policy in China,
Chinese parents are more doting upon their only child in the
family. Also, children's products like baby body lotion and food
are also favored by adults.
</P>
<P>
All of these indicate a great potential of children's market in
China. But the quality of some children's food products has been
questioned. A survey by the Shanghai Bureau of Quality and
Technical Supervision indicates that 70 percent of the examined
babies' food in Shanghai is yet up to standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
