<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Rejects Papua's Breakaway From Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said that the Indonesian government rejected the efforts to
separate Papua province (Iran Jaya) from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Papua National Congress which just ended on
Saturday in Jayapura, capital of the province, the president said
that most Papuans still wanted integration with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement at the Asian Church Council
meeting held Saturday in Tomohon, North Sulawesi, reports reaching
here Sunday said.
</P>
<P>
The Papua National Congress, which started on May 29, concluded
Saturday with a draft resolution, saying that the province
determined to separate from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The congress was attended by 2,700 participants from 14
districts in the province and some NGOs from several countries.
</P>
<P>
President Wahid has warned that the government will not
hesitate to take harsh action if the people in the province take
concrete measures to realize their independence aspiration.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said only a small number, those represented in the
congress, desired an independent state.
</P>
<P>
Separately, House of Representatives Speaker Akbar Tanjung
called on the government to remain alert towards the growing
aspirations of independence in the province.
</P>
<P>
"We should remain alert, Iran Jaya (Papua) could separate like
East Timor," he said, adding that "we can not tolerate a part of
the unitary state to separate."
</P>
<P>
Papua (Iran Jaya) is the largest island in Indonesia with a
population of about two million.
</P>
<P>
In 1963, then president Sukarno led Indonesia's fight to regain
the mineral-rich territory from the Netherlands. It was officially
integrated into Indonesia after a UN-sponsored plebiscite in 1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
