<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Set up Japanese Atrocities Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in north China's Hebei
Province set up a museum to inform the people of the atrocities
committed by Japanese invaders in China.
</P>
<P>
The museum, built to resemble the Japanese watch tower in China
during the War of Resistance Against Japan (1937-1945), was
entirely funded by local farmers themselves. It is surrounded by a
moat and iron bars, with a suspension bridge as the only entrance.
</P>
<P>
The museum was built near the site of the then Tunnel Warfare
in Ranzhuang, Qingyuan County, where local people defeated the
Japanese troops in underground tunnels stretching more than 3,000
meters. The Japanese set up 22 watch towers in a 15 sq.- km area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
