<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Regulations Protecting Ethnic Culture, Folk Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has formulated new regulations to protect its colorful ethnic
cultures and folk arts.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, which have been adopted by the standing
committee of the ninth provincial people's congress, will become
effective very soon.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has 25 ethnic groups, more than any other province in
China.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations put under legal protection all the
representative ethnic cultures and folk arts, ethnic festivals and
celebrations, traditional sports meets and recreational activities,
residences of various ethnic groups, garments and household
utensils, unique ethnic buildings and facilities.
</P>
<P>
The rules also protect manuscripts, Buddhist scriptures,
ancient books and records, documents, stone tablets and oral
histories, as well as all other aspects related to ethnic culture
and arts and crafts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000604.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Develops Colored Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Xinjiang, China's leading cotton
grower, has decided to expand this year's acreage of colored
cotton to 5,333 hectares and make Xinjiang the largest colored
cotton producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of Organic Agriculture predicts
that 30 percent of the cotton output around the globe will be
replaced by colored cotton in upcoming 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang experimented with growing colored cotton at Awat
County and the city of Shihezi in 1994. Colored cotton is
pollution-free, involving no bleaching and dying and sold two or
three times higher than the price of ordinary cotton. At present,
brown, green and light tan cottons are available on the local
market.
</P>
<P>
Tiancai Science and Technology Stock Company has developed a
long-fibre cotton ranging from 35 to 37 mm in length and new
cotton strains which resist cotton aphids and other diseases. The
company's output value of colored cotton surpassed 100 million
yuan last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000604.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Students Upbeat about Politics, Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese university students are
optimistic and supportive of the policies of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) and the government, according to results of a
national survey by the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted among tens of thousands of students at
75 universities in eight provinces and municipalities, including
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai, Hubei, Guangdong, Shaanxi, Jiangsu and
Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
Results showed that the major issues that the students watch
closely are U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in the former
Yugoslavia, the Invasion of the former Yugoslavia by U.S.-led NATO,
the "two countries theory" by Lee Teng-Hui of Taiwan, the signing
of Sino-U.S. agreement on China's accession to WTO, the
celebration ceremony of the 50th anniversary of the founding of
New China and the return of Macao to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The students gave positive comments on the government's work to
rejuvenate the nation through developing science and education,
crackdown on smuggling, curb deflation and appropriately handle
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
More students than in previous years are positive about the
government's efforts to reform and develop state-owned enterprises,
rule the country by law and build up an advanced culture.
</P>
<P>
Results of the survey show that the students think the central
government's decision to combat the "Falungong" cult is absolutely
necessary. Efforts to contain the evil sect have been successful.
</P>
<P>
Students highly praise the economic growth of the country and
are optimistic about future economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Students are eager to join the CPC, obtain master degrees, win
professional qualification and participate in social work and part
time jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
