<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The "Spring Bud" Program, a national endeavor that helps female
school dropouts in poor areas, has helped over 900,000 girl
students continue with their studies since it was launched in 1989.
</P>
<P>
An official with the China Children and Teenagers Fund (CCTF),
initiator of the program, said the program has collected over 300
million yuan (about 36 million U.S. dollars) in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Parents Expect Children to Win High Degrees
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that one-fourth of Chinese parents would
like their children to earn advanced degrees, while 36 percent
would be satisfied if their kids can get at least undergraduate
diplomas.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted among young parents in Beijing,
Shanghai, Guangzhou and Chongqing, which are all major big cities
in China. Results of the survey indicated that parents have much
higher expectation for their children than ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Parents More Professional in Infant Education
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted among 4,464 parents in four major Chinese
cities show that parents are becoming more professional in infant
education.
</P>
<P>
Healthy, intelligent, and reasonable kids are the favorite
among Chinese parents, according to the survey conducted in
Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and Chongqing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
