<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China made remarkable progress in pushing forward nine-year
compulsory education in 1999, said a report issued by the Ministry
of Education.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 80 percent of the country's population
available for compulsory education had received a nine-year
education.
</P>
<P>
Sino-U.S. Cooperation on Green Textbook
</P>
<P>
A cooperative project between Chinese and U.S.
environmentalists will soon bring a new textbook into Chinese
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, the Global Environmental Alliance China began
translating into Chinese "E 2: Environment and Education", a
textbook used in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Young Pioneers Hold Fourth National Congress
</P>
<P>
A total of 600 Chinese Young Pioneers (CYP) deputies from all
over the country gathered in Beijing to celebrate the
International Children's Day and attend the Fourth National
Congress of the CYP on June 1.
</P>
<P>
The Party and State Leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu Rongji,
Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing met the
deputies and warmly greeted all children from around the country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao said that all Chinese
youngsters will grow up together with the rapid development of
their motherland, while a promising new century is approaching. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
